{"cursor":"12605","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\nIn topology and related branches of mathematics, a 'Hausdorff space', 'separated\nspace' or 'T 2 space' is a topological space in which distinct points\nhave disjoint neighbourhoods. Of the many separation axioms that can be imposed\non a topological space, the \"Hausdorff condition\" (T 2) is the most\nfrequently used and discussed. It implies the uniqueness of limits of sequences,\nnets, and filters.\n\nHausdorff spaces are named after Felix Hausdorff, one of the founders of\ntopology. Hausdorff's original definition of a topological space (in 1914)\nincluded the Hausdorff condition as an axiom.\n","linknr":266,"url":"Hausdorff_space","recorded":1362477255,"links":39,"instances":["topology","topology","mathematics","topology","mathematics","topology","mathematics","topology","topology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Separation axioms","Topological spaces"],"headings":["Definitions","Equivalences","Examples and counterexamples","Properties","Preregularity versus regularity","Variants","Algebra of functions","Academic Humour","See also","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2a/Hausdorff_space.svg/200px-Hausdorff_space.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/3/0/a30832deeeb218245741603e7adacff9.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/3/9/33937d417198f06b078a324ff58cdbac.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/8/1/e81f6790ae7661514cf539650006fda9.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["neighbourhood","mathematics"],["net","topology"],["filter","topology"],["neighbourhood","topology"],["net","topology"],["filter","topology"],["neighbourhood","mathematics"],["subspace","topology"],["singleton","mathema